# Optional TypeScript Rules

## Statement

- Type names can be descriptive and explicit when that improves comprehension.
- Shared types may be colocated near the code that uses them when that makes navigation easier.
- Small, focused type aliases or interfaces can be preferred over large catch-all type definitions when that improves clarity.
- Function signatures and type shapes may stay simple and readable instead of becoming overly clever or dense.
- Shared types can be extracted when reuse or readability justifies the additional indirection.
- When it's aplicable, consider to use Enum for a set of related constants, and preserve the semantic meaning of the values and readability.

## Rationale

Optional TypeScript style choices can help keep code easier to read and navigate without turning every preference into a strict rule. Descriptive names, focused type definitions, and local organization patterns can make intent clearer and reduce the effort required to understand unfamiliar code.

Favoring readability over clever type construction can also improve long-term maintainability. Keeping abstractions small and extracting shared types only when they are genuinely useful helps preserve clarity while still allowing the codebase to grow in a consistent way.
